-- European shares edge lower, miners weigh
-- By Atul Prakash
-- Thu Aug 21, 2014 03:18AM EDT
-- None



LONDON, Aug 21 (Reuters) - European equities edged lower in early trading on Thursday, with  miners slipping after a disappointing manufacturing survey from China, the world's biggest metals consumer.

The STOXX Europe 600 Basic Resources index <.SXPP> fell 0.8 percent, the biggest sectoral decliner in Europe, after the HSBC/Markit Flash China Manufacturing Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) fell to 50.3 in August from July's 18-month high of 51.7, badly missing a Reuters forecast of 51.5. [ID:nL4N0QR1KW] Miners Rio Tinto <RIO.L>, BHP Billiton <BLT.L> and Antofagasta <ANTO.L> dropped 0.7 to 1.6 percent. The FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares <.FTEU3> fell 0.1 percent to 1,345.18 points by 0712 GMT.